    <div xml:id="PN235">
      <lg type="edition">
<l>ciṟiyakaṭ peṟiṉē yemakkīyu maṉṉē</l>
<l>periyakaṭ peṟiṉē</l>
<l>yāmpāṭat tāṉmakiḻn tuṇṇu maṉṉē</l>
<l>ciṟucōṟ ṟāṉu naṉipala kalattaṉ maṉṉē</l>
<l>peruñcōṟ ṟāṉu naṉipala kalattaṉ maṉṉē</l>
<l>yeṉpoṭu taṭipaṭu vaḻiyellā</l>
<l>memakkīyu maṉṉē</l>
<l>yampoṭu vēṉuḻai vaḻiyellān</l>
<l>tāṉiṟku maṉṉē</l>
<l>naranta nāṟun taṉkaiyāṟ</l>
<l>pulavunāṟu meṉṟalai taivaru maṉṉē</l>
<l>yaruntalai yirumpāṇa rakaṉmaṇṭait tuḷaiyurīi</l>
<l>yirappōr kaiyuḷum pōkip</l>
<l>purappōr puṉkaṇ pāvai cōra</l>
<l>vañcoṉuṇ ṭērccip pulavar nāviṟ</l>
<l>ceṉṟuvīḻn taṉṟava ṉaruniṟat tiṅkiya vēlē</l>
<l>yācā kentai yāṇṭuḷaṉ kollō</l>
<l>viṉippā ṭunaru millaip pāṭunark</l>
<l>koṉṟī kunaru millaip</l>
<l>paṉittuṟaip pakaṉṟai naṟaikkoṇ māmalar</l>
<l>cūṭātu vaikiyāṅkup piṟarkkoṉ</l>
<l>ṟīyātu vīyu muyirtavap palavē.</l>
</lg>
<lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>If helives [are] very many that will perish. (22)</l>
<l>obtains a little toddy, he will certainly give [it] to us. (1)</l>
<l> If he obtains much toddy, (2)</l>
<l> while we sing he will certainly enjoy [and] drink [it]. (3)</l>
<l> As one with a little rice he will certainly have very many plates (4)</l>
<l> and as one with much rice he will certainly have very many plates. (5)</l>
<l> All the befalling series(?) of meat with bones (6)</l>
<l> he will certainly give us. (7)</l>
<l> All the series of employing the spear along with the arrow (8) </l>
<l> he certainly will stand. (9)</l>
<l> With his hand fragrant of bitter orange (10)</l>
<l> he will certainly rub my head reeking of flesh. (11)</l>
<l> Piercing a hole in the wide bowl of great bards with rare heads (12)</l>
<l> going right through the hands of mendicants too, (13)</l>
<l> while the sorrowful dolls of those who keep them slip down, (14)</l>
<l> going into the tongue of poets with fine discrimination [and] pretty words, (15)</l>
<l> it has descended, the spear that has gone deep into his precious vital spot. (16)</l>
<l> [Our] father who is [our] support, where is he? (17)</l>
<l> Now there are none who sing and none who give something to those who sing. (18)</l>
<l> Like the big flower of the fragrant Pakaṉṟai from the dewy ghat (19)</l>
<l> that is kept without being worn, without giving anything to others (20a-21)</l>
<l> lives [are] very many that will perish. (22) </l>
</lg>
